Monday.title: Read Me: Getting Started with 80/20 Training
Monday.description: Thank you for using an 80/20 Training Plan! We are thrilled that you have chosen us and the 80/20 system. To get the most out of your plan, please review our Getting Started With 80/20 Training guide at www.8020endurance.com/resources

Monday.title: RF6 or Cross-Train
Monday.description: 5 minutes in Z1, 35 minutes Z2, 5 minutes Z1
Monday.coachComments:
Before you begin your training, be sure to review the Resources section at www.8020endurance.com/resources. Particularly recommended are the articles titled “Understanding Your 80/20 Run Plan” and “Intensity Guidelines for Running,” with details on managing days with cross-training options included in the former.
>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>
Discipline is required for the running foundation set. If rested, the temptation is to drift into Zone X. However, save your energy for the 20% of the 80/20 plan, and stay in Zone 1-2 for this workout. Avoid running with individuals who will tempt you to exceed Zone 2.

Tuesday.title: RF3 or Cross-Train
Tuesday.description: 5 minutes in Z1, 20 minutes Z2, 5 minutes Z1
Tuesday.coachComments: Discipline is required for the running foundation set. If rested, the temptation is to drift into Zone X. However, save your energy for the 20% of the 80/20 plan, and stay in Zone 1-2 for this workout. Avoid running with individuals who will tempt you to exceed Zone 2.

Tuesday.title: RAn5
Tuesday.description: 15 minutes Z1, 3 x (2.5 minutes Z4/5 minutes Z1) 7 minutes Z1
Tuesday.coachComments:
Wondering what Zone 1, Zone 2, and Zone 3 mean? Check out the document “Intensity Guidelines for Running” at www.8020endurance.com/resources.
>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>
When executed properly, this anaerobic interval set is the most effective method at increasing an athlete's VO2max. While VO2max is only one component an athlete's success, it is a direct predictor of endurance performance. Additionally, VO2 intervals have been proven to be more effective at improving overall economy than submaximal (threshold) or supramaximal intervals. Thus, a successful integration of these intervals in the General phase of training places the athlete in an advantageous position for the upcoming Specific phase, and ultimately their endurance performance results. These intervals are challenging, and the athlete must take great care to not perform them at a Zone 3 or Zone 5 intensity. The unusually high rest period compared to a Zone 3 work reflects the difficulty of the interval. The 80/20 principle is fundamental to executing these anaerobic intervals, as the athlete has deliberately trained easy 80% of the time in order to have the form necessary to maintain this repeated Zone 4 intensity. These anaerobic intervals are permission to go very hard. Be bold, but measured. A successful anaerobic interval set will have the athlete's output (pace, speed, power) be almost identical for each interval, in Zone 4, and without fade.

Friday.title: RSP7
Friday.description: 5 minutes Z1, 5 minutes Z2, 7 x (1 minute Z4/2 minutes Z1) 5 minutes Z1
Friday.coachComments:
Be sure to review the Resources section at www.8020endurance.com/resources. Particularly recommended are the articles titled “Understanding Your 80/20 Run Plan” and “Intensity Guidelines for Running,” with details on managing days with cross-training options included in the former.
>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>
Not to be confused with the Zone 5 running short interval (RSI), running speed play is done in Zone 4 with much shorter recoveries. If done in Zone 5, the athlete will fade.

Sunday.title: RL5
Sunday.description: 1 mile Run Zone 1, 8.5 miles Run Zone 2, 0.5 mile Run Zone 1
Sunday.coachComments:
Be sure to review the Resources section at www.8020endurance.com/resources. Particularly recommended are the articles titled “Understanding Your 80/20 Run Plan” and “Intensity Guidelines for Running,” with details on managing days with cross-training options included in the former.
>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>
Similar to the frequent Run Foundation workout, the Long Run is measured by distance to ensure the athlete experiences the required stress. Upper Zone 2 is recommended. Half and full marathon athletes may benefit from a rare Zone X exception and spend a majority of their time in Zone X for this workout. Every effort should be made to "negative split" the workout, where the second half of the run is slightly faster than the first half. Complete this workout by distance only, any planned time associated with this workout is a broad estimate.

Tuesday.title: RFF6
Tuesday.description: 5 minutes Run Zone 1, 30 minutes Run Zone 2, 12 minutes Run Zone 3
Tuesday.coachComments: One of the few workouts designed with the intensity scheduled for the end of the workout, the intent is to expose the athlete to high intensity while slightly fatigued. An excellent simulation of a strong race finish.

Wednesday.title: RF5 or Cross-Train
Wednesday.description: 5 minutes in Z1, 30 minutes Z2, 5 minutes Z1
Wednesday.coachComments: Discipline is required for the running foundation set. If rested, the temptation is to drift into Zone X. However, save your energy for the 20% of the 80/20 plan, and stay in Zone 1-2 for this workout. Avoid running with individuals who will tempt you to exceed Zone 2.

Thursday.title: RSP3
Thursday.description: 5 minutes Z1, 5 minutes Z2, 5 x (1 minute Z4/2 minutes Z1) 5 minutes Z1
Thursday.coachComments: Not to be confused with the Zone 5 running short interval (RSI), running speed play is done in Zone 4 with much shorter recoveries. If done in Zone 5, the athlete will fade.

Saturday.title: RTa1
Saturday.coachComments: Brief, but fast intervals to promote the taper.
